Date: 0/0/1911
Source: Diary
Author: JAMIESON
Vol / Page: 27
Edition:
Quote: In those days of my childhood it was all China tea, the common kind went by the name of post and rail. 'Post and rail' meant it was more stem and very little leaf.
Notes: in Jamieson (1916) Old Memories

Date: 0/0/1940
Source: Te Waimate
Author: STUDHOLME
Vol / Page: 91
Edition:
Quote: .. bread cost only 6d. or 7d. a 4lb. loaf, and tea (post and rails) could be bought for 1/- per lb.
Notes: from 1954 edition: Many of the old station cooks, with the assistance of an `offsider' (mate) found no difficulty in cooking for fifty or sixty men. .. it has to be remembered that .. bread cost only 6d. or 7d. a 4lb. loaf, and tea (post and rails) could be bought for 1/- per lb. Some of these contract cooks were great fossickers and managed to find quite a lot of green stuff for vegetables ...

